Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken
Comment: Short version: it's what's known as a "loss leader". This is when a store intentionally sells a product for less than what it costs them to put it on the shelf in order to attract customers who will usually buy something else while they're there. Grocery stores do this with milk.

Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken
Comment: Lots of stores do this. I worked at Best Buy when the PlayStation 3 came out. I noticed we were actually selling them for a little less than what we were purchasing them for. Some of the computers too. Turns out the profit margins are so high on the accessories and games that they were willing to take a small loss if it meant another consumer to buy all of those extras.

Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken
Comment: I'm a Sam's Club member.  One year my boss gave all his employees $100 gift card to Costco as part of our Christmas bonus. I used over half of my card to simply purchase the rotisserie whole chicken. My card lasted me into the start of summer. Their chicken tastes better than Sam's IMO.

Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken

Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken

Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken
Comment:
It's no different conceptually then what Winco does with their fried chicken. They place the section in a section of the store that makes it clear you walk by as much items as possible, to entice potential additional purchases. And in Wincos case, they keep their prices low by requiring certain fried chicken sets (we add these drums and wings for example always at a specific ratio) and to minimize waste as well. They also sell their fried chicken cold for a often more expensive price. 
Just wanted to bring it up because I considered similar context, and also I know there's other viewers out there that go to Winco Foods that dont often consider that factor in the northwest.

Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken

Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken

The reason why they sold the roasted chicken and cheap hot dogs was because of the long travel time for its customers.  Back when they started Costco's were sparse.  And sometimes you'd have to drive 45 minutes or more on the interstate. The cheap food sold at a loss was something for it's customers between the shopping and the long travel home.  The rotisserie chicken was also part of that idea.  A take away to be enjoyed at home for cheap.  Also, back in the early 90's, the chicken was 3.99.

Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken
Comment: In other words, the chicken price and the demand for those chickens have hit equilibrium, which is when the market price of quantity of goods supplied is equal to the quantity of goods demanded at said price. This is the point at which the demand and supply curves in the market intersect, and it's also where profit is maximized. That's why it's not always better to raise prices or lower them.

Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken
Comment: The reason the cooked ones are cheaper is because most people don't go buy 6 months worth of chicken when it's already cooked. Costco wants you to keep coming back and buying a freshly cooked chicken and just about everything else you see.  If you stock up on uncooked chicken, it's unlikely you'll be back in multiple times for other items.

Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken
Comment: Both the rotisserie chicken and the hot dog/soda deal are “loss leaders” because, while you are there, you’ll spend 2 to 3 hundred dollars on regular costco stuff.  Love costco, but that’s why the chicken and hot dogs stay so cheap.

Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken

Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken

Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken

Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken
Comment: So the Chicken that comes into Costco for the rotisserie, is soaked in a brine solution before being frozen and sent to Costco. Let's say it's been a slow day, and they pull the chickens that they don't want to sell to members any more, but are still good to eat. They flash chill the chickens, and then reuse the chicken for other items at Costco. You might find a tray of 6 drumsticks for $5, You might like our Chicken noodle soup, or our Chicken salad. also there are packages of just pure white meat chicken already cooked for you to use in a dish of your choosing. The only food that could be thrown out is when we make trays of chicken wings or ribs, which we normally save for the busier weekends. Sometimes the chickens are under the 3 pound weight and we'll even mark them down because of this. And that chicken farm she mentioned is only going to help Costco be able to sustain 40 percent of its supply chain. We are hoping that by doing this we can have a steadier supply of 3 pound chickens so we don't have to mark them down.

I’m just as guilty because I know this and at time I cave in and buy one to make my own life easier. The guilt piles on as I start to see the bone structure of these poor animals. It’s so damn sad but who cares about stupid children’s, right? Well, we should ALL care!

Title: The Big Problem Costco Shoppers Are Currently Having With Their Rotisserie Chickens
Comment: I never bought Costco's rotisserie chicken, but this whole topic made me curious, so I bought one today. I can definitely understand where people are coming from. There was subtle chemical taste, which may not be noticed by most people. I also noticed that there was a part of the leg that was particularly strong in chemical taste. I read a comment somewhere that it was a cleaning chemical Costco used to disinfect rotating rods. I'm inclined to believe this. I think the part of the leg was wrapped around the rod and picked up more of the chemical flavor. If this is what's causing the issue, then it may be best to buy their chicken later in the day. I bought mine at 11 AM.

Title: The Big Problem Costco Shoppers Are Currently Having With Their Rotisserie Chickens
Comment: There is a chemical taste I have been noticing in foods of all types for over forty years. This taste is due to a disinfectant that is used to clean equipment and preparation surfaces, and I don't believe it is chlorine bleach. They wipe down surfaces with this stuff, whatever it is, then fail to rinse or wipe down with plain water. A soft-serve ice cream place that I once frequented made a batch without rinsing the cleaner out of the equipment. It was uneatable. I threw it away, and never went back. Some places like Taco Bell and pizza joints slide the food down the stainless steel counter, and the food picks-up the off taste if cleaning was improperly done.  Food service workers may have even been told they don't need to rinse after using this product. A quick look at food service disinfectants sold on Amazon show that they brag about not needing rinsing. Sure, if you don't mind your food tasting like disinfectant.

Hyperinsulinemia activates angiotensin II rennin causes kidneys to increase blood pressure.  Electrolytes imbalance of magnesium and potassium will result in hypertension as well.  But it's much easier to blame sodium than address the real cause.

Title: Removing Meat from a Costco Rotisserie Chicken
Comment: As I've seen in a few previous comments, I take every scrap and juices you put back in the container to discard, and boil them with some spices, onions and garlic to make a flavorful enough broth to make about 6-8 litres of chicken stock! The minor remaining meat on those bones falls off into the broth and you've got an insane broth for a winter day homemade chicken soup.

Title: Removing Meat from a Costco Rotisserie Chicken
Comment: Don't throw the bones and drippings out!  That's liquid gold! It makes amazing chicken bone broth!

Title: Removing Meat from a Costco Rotisserie Chicken
Comment: The leftover juice and bones can be used for soup; that's what I do with that.   Add rice and a can of Tomato, Corn, and Okra and I'm a happy camper.   Since the wing tips are small, use that in the soup as well.   The rest I use either for meals outright or make, for instance, Fettuccine Alfredo with broccoli with the meat.   So many uses for rotisserie chicken and, in my case Sam's version, saves me a lot of money in meals.   :)

Title: Removing Meat from a Costco Rotisserie Chicken
Comment:
Thank You for showing me how to not spend 30 minutes deboning a chicken!  

I save the debris (skin, bones, and juice in the container) as the start for a chicken and sausage gumbo by placing it into a pot, adding enough water (or boxed chicken stock) to cover it and simmer for 30+ minutes.  Pour the debris and liquid through a fine mesh strainer, placed over a large measuring cup.  Discard the debris, let the liquid cool, cover, and place in the fridge for a few hours or overnight and the next day skim the fat from the top.  At this point I either freeze the liquid or add it to my roux, along with the reserved chicken meat and continue cooking my gumbo.

They quickly convinced me to never darken Home Depot's doorways again. They often sell identical items for much cheaper and their variety of goods is much better than at the nearby Home Depot. I can't tell you how many times, before Menards came to town, that I would find myself in the Home Depot parking lot ordering what I needed from Amazon because I had just walked out of Home Depot without finding what I was after.  Nowadays, so much of the Home Depot inventory is kept behind locked bars, if they actually have what you want, but you can't get an employee to unlock it, you can't buy it. Somehow Menards manages to do it without locking anything up. If Home Depot wants to make their future earnings targets, they better start remembering who their customers are. If Homer is looking for me, he can find me at Menards.

Comment:
Some of my fast and yummy rotisserie chicken dishes are:

Chicken cheese crusted quesadilla. You can use extra Taco Bell sauce packets or whatever you like… toss your shredded chicken in some sauce (I typically use one packet of mild and one Hot per dilla.) add Mexican cheese and cook on medium. Once it’s almost finished, lift up the dilla and sprinkle some extra cheese in the pan and drop the dilla on top. Don’t touch it, just watch the edges and once it’s crisp shake it loose and repeat for the second side.

That's what we kids did, we'd be shakin' bottles in the morning, so the dressing tasted best for dinner, the "Slab Salad" we did that with Ranch AND AVOCADO ( I was in Southern California we had Avocado trees in our yards). I do like Blue Cheese better, but at the time "Ranch" was so new and exciting...

Comment:
Me: takes one chicken, debones it, uses the bones in a stock and let's it seep overnight. Uses half the meat shreds in a chicken salad and the rest in a soup the next night with the stock.
The second chicken, I de bone and make more stock but freeze it for later in the winter. Use the meat from that bird in a jambalaya.
Jambalaya is versatile but it feeds many and can stretch to different meals, as can soup and gumbo.
